        "subtype": "bot_message",
        "text": "*[Bug 19069] aperm(X, 1:length(dim(X))) should short-circuit and just return X.*\n<https:\/\/bugs.r-project.org\/show_bug.cgi?id=19069>\n\n--- Comment #6 from Pavel N. Krivitsky (<mailto:p.krivitsky@unsw.edu.au|p.krivitsky@unsw.edu.au>) ---\nIndeed, looks like `aperm()` strips attributes such as `class`, which is indeed\ncontrary to the documentation, but it means that this behaviour is different\ndepending on the permutation.\n\n### R-trunk + patch:\n``` r\ndata(Titanic)\na &lt;- structure(Titanic, class = \"blah\")\naperm(a, 1:4, resize = TRUE) |&gt; class()\n#&gt; [1] \"blah\"\naperm(a, 4:1, resize = TRUE) |&gt; class()\n#&gt; [1] \"array\"\n```\n\n### R 4.5.3:\n``` r\ndata(Titanic)\na &lt;- structure(Titanic, class = \"blah\")\naperm(a, 1:4, resize = TRUE) |&gt; class()\n#&gt; [1] \"array\"\naperm(a, 4:1, resize = TRUE) |&gt; class()\n#&gt; [1] \"array\"\n```\n\nAs far as I can tell, this is what causes the problem in the `tourr` package:\nthe input is of a class with a `[` method, and if the class isn't stripped, it\ngets called inside `apply()` and breaks.",
        "username": "r-bugs notifier",
        "icons": {
            "emoji": ":robot_face:"
        },
